<article about="/us/blog/threat-insight/jssloader-recoded-and-reloaded" class="node--type--blog-post node--view-mode--full node node-blog-full _legacy_content _blog-full">
  



  <div class="breadcrumbs _legacy_element _breadcrumbs"><div class="nav-crumbs"><div class="breadcrumb__item"><a href="/us/blog" class="breadcrum__item-link">Blog</a></div><div class="breadcrumb__item"><a href="/us/blog/threat-insight" class="breadcrum__item-link">Threat Insight</a></div><div class="breadcrumb__item">
            JSSLoader: Recoded and Reloaded          </div></div></div>

  <div class="blog-banner">
    <div class="blog-banner__image">      <picture>
                  <source srcset="/sites/default/files/styles/image_1920_750/public/blog-banners/pfpt-ac-blog-banner-5.jpg.webp?itok=qGRdtlGt 1x" media="screen and (min-width: 1440px)" type="image/webp" width="1920" height="750"/>
              <source srcset="/sites/default/files/styles/image_1024_400/public/blog-banners/pfpt-ac-blog-banner-5.jpg.webp?itok=a4lurQ0l 1x" media="screen and (min-width: 1024px)" type="image/webp" width="1024" height="400"/>
              <source srcset="/sites/default/files/styles/image_768_375/public/blog-banners/pfpt-ac-blog-banner-5.jpg.webp?itok=q7z--dmb 1x" media="screen and (min-width: 768px)" type="image/webp" width="768" height="375"/>
              <source srcset="/sites/default/files/styles/image_1920_750/public/blog-banners/pfpt-ac-blog-banner-5.jpg.webp?itok=qGRdtlGt 1x" media="screen and (min-width: 1440px)" type="image/webp" width="1920" height="750"/>
              <source srcset="/sites/default/files/styles/image_1024_400/public/blog-banners/pfpt-ac-blog-banner-5.jpg.webp?itok=a4lurQ0l 1x" media="screen and (min-width: 1024px)" type="image/webp" width="1024" height="400"/>
              <source srcset="/sites/default/files/styles/image_768_375/public/blog-banners/pfpt-ac-blog-banner-5.jpg.webp?itok=q7z--dmb 1x" media="screen and (min-width: 768px)" type="image/webp" width="768" height="375"/>
                  <img loading="lazy" src="/sites/default/files/styles/image_768_300/public/blog-banners/pfpt-ac-blog-banner-5.jpg.webp?itok=gkgvhOvS" width="768" height="300" alt="Archiving and Compliance" typeof="foaf:Image" />

  </picture>


</div>
    <div class="blog-banner__gradient-overlay"></div>
    <div class="blog-banner__heading-wrap">
      
      


<h1 class="blog-banner__heading">
      <span>JSSLoader: Recoded and Reloaded </span>

  </h1>

    </div>
  </div>

  <div class="blog-content">
    <div class="blog-content__sharethis sharethis_toolbox sharethis_32x32_style">
      <div class="blog-content__sharethis_label sharethis__label">Share with your network!</div>
      <div class="blog-content__sharethis_buttons sharethis_buttons">
        <div class="sharethis-inline-share-buttons"></div>
        
<span class="addthis_button_subscribe at300b UNCONVERTED" title=Subscribe>
  <span class="at-icon-wrapper block-subscribe-button__trigger block-subscribe-button__addthis"></span>
</span>


      </div>
    </div>
        <div class="blog-content__metadata blog-content__metadata-author">
      <span class="blog-content__date">  <time datetime="2021-06-24T11:22:08Z">June 24, 2021</time>

</span>
        <span class="blog-content__author">
                Dennis Schwarz, Matthew Mesa and Crista Giering
  
        </span>
    </div>
    <div class="node-full__body blog-content__body">  <h3 paraeid="{e5c122cc-8ada-4396-aa82-19b76124309b}{183}" paraid="967145192">Key Takeaways&nbsp;</h3>

<ul>
	<li>After a months-long absence, the malware loader&nbsp;JSSLoader&nbsp;returned in June 2021 campaigns rewritten from the .NET programming language to C++.&nbsp;</li>
	<li>Rewriting the <a href="https://www.proofpoint.com/us/threat-reference/malware">malware</a>&nbsp;could be an effort by threat actors to evade current detections.&nbsp;</li>
	<li>Current&nbsp;TA543&nbsp;campaigns&nbsp;delivering&nbsp;JSSLoader&nbsp;are&nbsp;using similar lures&nbsp;to those observed by Proofpoint researchers in 2019&nbsp;and&nbsp;the emails&nbsp;continue to&nbsp;contain links to a TDS landing page.&nbsp;</li>
</ul>

<h3 paraeid="{e5c122cc-8ada-4396-aa82-19b76124309b}{232}" paraid="765112119">Overview&nbsp;</h3>

<p paraeid="{e5c122cc-8ada-4396-aa82-19b76124309b}{242}" paraid="1263864377">In June 2021,&nbsp;Proofpoint researchers observed a new variant of the downloader&nbsp;JSSLoader&nbsp;in several campaigns impacting a variety of organizations. This version of the malware loader&nbsp;was&nbsp;rewritten from .NET to the C++ programming language. This change, while not unheard of, is not a common occurrence and could be an effort by the threat actors utilizing&nbsp;JSSLoader&nbsp;to evade current detections.&nbsp;JSSLoader&nbsp;is often dropped in the first or second stage of a campaign and has the functionality to profile infected machines and load additional payloads.&nbsp;&nbsp;</p>

<p paraeid="{2d22d5cd-8eab-4f9f-ad4d-c757b6695baf}{1}" paraid="1989943031">The campaigns are ongoing and&nbsp;use&nbsp;similar&nbsp;lures&nbsp;to those initially observed by Proofpoint researchers in 2019. According to our data, the recent campaigns have&nbsp;attempted to target&nbsp;as many as&nbsp;several&nbsp;hundred organizations at a time across a wide range of&nbsp;industries, including finance, manufacturing, technology, retail, healthcare, education, and transportation.&nbsp;</p>

<h3 paraeid="{2d22d5cd-8eab-4f9f-ad4d-c757b6695baf}{21}" paraid="1664059137">Malware Analysis&nbsp;</h3>

<p paraeid="{2d22d5cd-8eab-4f9f-ad4d-c757b6695baf}{29}" paraid="1619933966">Proofpoint researchers initially observed&nbsp;<a href="https://malpedia.caad.fkie.fraunhofer.de/details/win.jssloader" rel="noreferrer noopener" target="_blank">JSSLoader</a>&nbsp;in September 2019. It was written in .NET at the time and being actively developed. Fast forward nearly two years and Proofpoint has now identified this latest variant of the malware loader written in C++. It has much of the same functionality as previous iterations.&nbsp;The following provides a&nbsp;more in-depth&nbsp;look at that early version and the changes the loader has undergone since 2019.&nbsp;</p>

<h4 paraeid="{2d22d5cd-8eab-4f9f-ad4d-c757b6695baf}{43}" paraid="1314264796">2019&nbsp;Version of&nbsp;JSSLoader&nbsp;(.NET)&nbsp;</h4>

<p paraeid="{2d22d5cd-8eab-4f9f-ad4d-c757b6695baf}{55}" paraid="1117500070">JSSLoader&nbsp;is an initial access malware&nbsp;that&nbsp;was written in .NET and was named after its JSS namespace and jssAdmin command and control (C&amp;C) panel login page:&nbsp;</p>

<p paraeid="{2d22d5cd-8eab-4f9f-ad4d-c757b6695baf}{66}" paraid="1780572875">&nbsp;</p>

<p paraeid="{2d22d5cd-8eab-4f9f-ad4d-c757b6695baf}{68}" paraid="500691826"><img alt="Graphical user interface, application, website

Description automatically generated" src="data:image/png;base64," unselectable="on">&nbsp;</p>

<p paraeid="{2d22d5cd-8eab-4f9f-ad4d-c757b6695baf}{71}" paraid="10685670"><em>Figure&nbsp;1.&nbsp;JSSLoader&nbsp;C&amp;C panel login page from September&nbsp;27,&nbsp;2019&nbsp;version.&nbsp;</em></p>

<p paraeid="{2d22d5cd-8eab-4f9f-ad4d-c757b6695baf}{85}" paraid="1286786883">Its C&amp;C used HTTPS requests with base64-encoded data:&nbsp;</p>

<p paraeid="{2d22d5cd-8eab-4f9f-ad4d-c757b6695baf}{91}" paraid="133208370"><img alt="A picture containing text

Description automatically generated" src="data:image/png;base64," unselectable="on">&nbsp;</p>

<p paraeid="{2d22d5cd-8eab-4f9f-ad4d-c757b6695baf}{94}" paraid="875672860"><em>Figure&nbsp;2.&nbsp;Example C&amp;C request from September 27,&nbsp;2019&nbsp;version.&nbsp;</em></p>

<p paraeid="{2d22d5cd-8eab-4f9f-ad4d-c757b6695baf}{108}" paraid="805431692">The initial C&amp;C beacon contained verbose system information:&nbsp;</p>

<p paraeid="{2d22d5cd-8eab-4f9f-ad4d-c757b6695baf}{114}" paraid="1833327490"><img alt="Table

Description automatically generated" src="data:image/png;base64," unselectable="on">&nbsp;</p>

<p paraeid="{2d22d5cd-8eab-4f9f-ad4d-c757b6695baf}{117}" paraid="1060206323"><em>Figure&nbsp;3.&nbsp;Example system information (trimmed for readability) from September 27,&nbsp;2019&nbsp;version.&nbsp;</em></p>

<p paraeid="{2d22d5cd-8eab-4f9f-ad4d-c757b6695baf}{131}" paraid="1971242889">Its commands and functionality focused on executing a next stage&nbsp;executable&nbsp;or JavaScript:&nbsp;</p>

<p paraeid="{2d22d5cd-8eab-4f9f-ad4d-c757b6695baf}{137}" paraid="1126836439"><img alt="Text

Description automatically generated" src="data:image/png;base64," unselectable="on">&nbsp;</p>

<p paraeid="{2d22d5cd-8eab-4f9f-ad4d-c757b6695baf}{140}" paraid="1131260008"><em>Figure&nbsp;4.&nbsp;Commands from September 27,&nbsp;2019&nbsp;version.&nbsp;</em></p>

<h4 paraeid="{2d22d5cd-8eab-4f9f-ad4d-c757b6695baf}{152}" paraid="1781394119">2020-2021&nbsp;JSSLoader&nbsp;Changes&nbsp;(.NET)&nbsp;</h4>

<p paraeid="{2d22d5cd-8eab-4f9f-ad4d-c757b6695baf}{160}" paraid="742504828">Since the initial version of&nbsp;JSSLoader, there have been gradual changes and improvements to the malware in successive campaigns.&nbsp;Morphisec&nbsp;wrote about some of these in a January 2021 paper titled <a href="https://www.morphisec.com/hubfs/eBooks_and_Whitepapers/FIN7%20JSSLOADER%20FINAL%20WEB.pdf" rel="noreferrer noopener" target="_blank">Threat Profile the Evolution of the FIN7&nbsp;JSSLoader&nbsp;(PDF)</a>. Two of the most visible changes were a switch from the verbose system information to a JSON object and the addition of new commands.&nbsp;For&nbsp;example, the&nbsp;JSSLoader&nbsp;used in a December 14,&nbsp;2020&nbsp;email-based campaign sent the following system information:&nbsp;</p>

<p paraeid="{2d22d5cd-8eab-4f9f-ad4d-c757b6695baf}{183}" paraid="1811582640"><img alt="Text, letter

Description automatically generated" src="data:image/png;base64," unselectable="on">&nbsp;</p>

<p paraeid="{2d22d5cd-8eab-4f9f-ad4d-c757b6695baf}{188}" paraid="104913554"><em>Figure&nbsp;5.&nbsp;Example system information (formatted and trimmed for readability) from December 14,&nbsp;2020&nbsp;version.&nbsp;</em></p>

<p paraeid="{2d22d5cd-8eab-4f9f-ad4d-c757b6695baf}{204}" paraid="137694016">While the formatting changed, the beacon contained&nbsp;much of the same information&nbsp;as the&nbsp;original version. In addition to the changes in the C&amp;C protocol, several new commands were added. The focus of the new commands was still on executing a next stage:&nbsp;</p>

<p paraeid="{2d22d5cd-8eab-4f9f-ad4d-c757b6695baf}{214}" paraid="284983809"><img alt="Text

Description automatically generated" src="data:image/png;base64," unselectable="on">&nbsp;</p>

<p paraeid="{2d22d5cd-8eab-4f9f-ad4d-c757b6695baf}{219}" paraid="1108617809"><em>Figure&nbsp;6.&nbsp;Commands from December 14,&nbsp;2020&nbsp;version.&nbsp;</em></p>

<p paraeid="{2d22d5cd-8eab-4f9f-ad4d-c757b6695baf}{235}" paraid="743272734">After this December 2020 campaign, activity paused and the malware went through a redevelopment phase, according to Proofpoints visibility.&nbsp;</p>

<h4 paraeid="{41bd1b9a-4626-4b65-bb15-0e6bc2e1c5f9}{144}" paraid="1791860639">June 2021&nbsp;JSSLoader&nbsp;(C++)&nbsp;</h4>

<p paraeid="{41bd1b9a-4626-4b65-bb15-0e6bc2e1c5f9}{163}" paraid="1160442594">In June 2021, email campaigns resumed, but the&nbsp;JSSLoader&nbsp;malware had been redeveloped from using the .NET programming language to C++ (this change was also&nbsp;<a href="https://twitter.com/Arkbird_SOLG/status/1400845449515372555" rel="noreferrer noopener" target="_blank">noticed on infosec Twitter</a>). It is not common for a malware to be redeveloped in a different programming language, but it does happen occasionally. Proofpoint recently&nbsp;<a href="https://www.proofpoint.com/us/blog/threat-insight/new-variant-buer-loader-written-rust" rel="noreferrer noopener" target="_blank">documented</a>&nbsp;another&nbsp;initial access&nbsp;malware known as Buer&nbsp;Loader that was redeveloped from the C programming language to Rust. As noted in that blog post, rewriting a malware can enable threat actors to better evade existing detection capabilities.&nbsp;</p>

<p paraeid="{06db08d7-acfb-48bd-a122-e248fb80e970}{6}" paraid="464819106">The C++ version of&nbsp;JSSLoader&nbsp;analyzed&nbsp;here is&nbsp;from a June 8,&nbsp;2021&nbsp;email-based campaign. It sets up registry run persistence using a value name of AppJSSLoader and has similar style of system information beacon as the later .NET versions:&nbsp;</p>

<p paraeid="{06db08d7-acfb-48bd-a122-e248fb80e970}{18}" paraid="1324078778"><img alt="Text, letter

Description automatically generated" src="data:image/png;base64," unselectable="on">&nbsp;</p>

<p paraeid="{06db08d7-acfb-48bd-a122-e248fb80e970}{21}" paraid="1218022327"><em>Figure&nbsp;7.&nbsp;Example system information (formatted and trimmed for readability) from June 8,&nbsp;2021&nbsp;C++ version.&nbsp;</em></p>

<p paraeid="{06db08d7-acfb-48bd-a122-e248fb80e970}{37}" paraid="2076868505">The C++ version also has similar command functionality, though they switched from the Cmd prefix of the later .NET versions back to the Task prefix seen in the earlier .NET samples:&nbsp;</p>

<p paraeid="{06db08d7-acfb-48bd-a122-e248fb80e970}{43}" paraid="1035956482"><img alt="Graphical user interface

Description automatically generated with medium confidence" src="data:image/png;base64," unselectable="on">&nbsp;</p>

<p paraeid="{06db08d7-acfb-48bd-a122-e248fb80e970}{46}" paraid="1947312098"><em>Figure&nbsp;8.&nbsp;Commands from June 8,&nbsp;2021&nbsp;C++ version.&nbsp;</em></p>

<p paraeid="{2d715720-139a-4201-b10b-737bf7d217d0}{69}" paraid="1660893888">C&amp;C protocol and command similarity&nbsp;was&nbsp;likely a choice to remain backwards compatible with the existing .NET&nbsp;versions&nbsp;C&amp;C panel software.&nbsp;</p>

<h3 paraeid="{06db08d7-acfb-48bd-a122-e248fb80e970}{62}" paraid="1326285953">Campaign&nbsp;Details&nbsp;</h3>

<p paraeid="{06db08d7-acfb-48bd-a122-e248fb80e970}{70}" paraid="1177370959">JSSLoader&nbsp;appears to be exclusive to several&nbsp;threat actors. In fact, Proofpoint has only&nbsp;observed&nbsp;two actors using it since&nbsp;the first email campaign in 2019.&nbsp;&nbsp;</p>

<p paraeid="{06db08d7-acfb-48bd-a122-e248fb80e970}{88}" paraid="541306518">Most of the campaigns&nbsp;were&nbsp;attributed to&nbsp;the threat actor tracked by Proofpoint as&nbsp;TA543. They&nbsp;are characterized by their&nbsp;widespread&nbsp;distribution with opportunistic targeting.&nbsp;A typical campaign contains thousands of email messages and targets several hundred organizations.&nbsp;The lures used by TA543&nbsp;typically focus on&nbsp;invoices and delivery information of packages.&nbsp;&nbsp;</p>

<p paraeid="{06db08d7-acfb-48bd-a122-e248fb80e970}{98}" paraid="173327160">The following&nbsp;sections describe&nbsp;and compare the&nbsp;original&nbsp;campaigns observed by Proofpoint in 2019&nbsp;to&nbsp;the&nbsp;June 2021&nbsp;campaigns.&nbsp;</p>

<h4 paraeid="{06db08d7-acfb-48bd-a122-e248fb80e970}{108}" paraid="1138929380">September 2019 Campaign Example&nbsp;</h4>

<p paraeid="{1cfc9874-6a65-440c-af42-bd1ceaa852d2}{237}" paraid="1888735856">On&nbsp;September&nbsp;27,&nbsp;2019&nbsp;Proofpoint analysts observed a TA543 campaign spoofing Intuit&nbsp;branding.&nbsp;The threat actor used a likely compromised account for an email marketing service to send the malicious emails that purported to be invoices and&nbsp;contained URLs linking to a landing page hosting&nbsp;BlackTDS.&nbsp;The TDS would direct the user to the download another file, a VBS downloader, hosted on SharePoint. The VBS downloader would then download&nbsp;JSSLoader.&nbsp;</p>

<p paraeid="{f107ef82-a005-4f67-8a31-aee579703b70}{193}" paraid="985373439">During our analysis of&nbsp;JSSLoader, it additionally loaded a Griffon payload which is historically associated with another actor, TA3546, also known as FIN7 or&nbsp;Carbanak.&nbsp;In the following months&nbsp;Proofpoint analysts&nbsp;observed TA543 shift to primarily delivering&nbsp;JSSLoader&nbsp;and/or other loaders that were often observed downloading other TA3546-associated payloads.&nbsp;</p>

<p paraeid="{06db08d7-acfb-48bd-a122-e248fb80e970}{162}" paraid="1226801141"><img alt="Graphical user interface, application, Teams

Description automatically generated" src="data:image/png;base64," unselectable="on">&nbsp;</p>

<p paraeid="{06db08d7-acfb-48bd-a122-e248fb80e970}{165}" paraid="1484563944"><em>Figure&nbsp;9.&nbsp;TA543 email that leads&nbsp;to the download of&nbsp;JSSLoader.&nbsp;</em></p>

<h4 paraeid="{06db08d7-acfb-48bd-a122-e248fb80e970}{185}" paraid="1924348186">June 2021 Campaign Example&nbsp;</h4>

<p paraeid="{06db08d7-acfb-48bd-a122-e248fb80e970}{195}" paraid="1145527163">On June 8, 2021,&nbsp;Proofpoint analysts&nbsp;observed a TA543 campaign spoofing&nbsp;UPS&nbsp;branding (Figure&nbsp;10). The email contained&nbsp;URLs&nbsp;linking&nbsp;to a&nbsp;Keitaro&nbsp;TDS landing.&nbsp;In turn,&nbsp;the landing linked&nbsp;to the download of a Windows Scripting File (WSF) hosted on&nbsp;SharePoint. If executed, it downloaded&nbsp;an intermediate script,&nbsp;which then downloaded&nbsp;and executed&nbsp;the C++ version of&nbsp;JSSLoader.&nbsp;</p>

<p paraeid="{06db08d7-acfb-48bd-a122-e248fb80e970}{219}" paraid="1243314451"><img alt="Graphical user interface, application

Description automatically generated" src="data:image/png;base64," unselectable="on">&nbsp;</p>

<p paraeid="{06db08d7-acfb-48bd-a122-e248fb80e970}{224}" paraid="825648984"><em>Figure&nbsp;10.&nbsp;TA543 email sample&nbsp;from&nbsp;June 8, 2021, that leads to the&nbsp;download&nbsp;of&nbsp;JSSLoader.&nbsp;</em></p>

<h3 paraeid="{06db08d7-acfb-48bd-a122-e248fb80e970}{240}" paraid="1754310150">Conclusion&nbsp;</h3>

<p paraeid="{06db08d7-acfb-48bd-a122-e248fb80e970}{250}" paraid="1255885557">The threat actors behind&nbsp;JSSLoader&nbsp;have continuously made modifications since its debut in 2019 and are likely to continue doing so using the 2021 variant. With the redevelopment of the malware into C++, which was possibly&nbsp;done&nbsp;to evade current detections and make analysis more difficult, Proofpoint researchers have not seen the .NET version in play. Instead, researchers anticipate seeing small refinements being made to the 2021 version in future campaigns, keeping in line with the evolution of the .NET version over the past two years.&nbsp;</p>

<p paraeid="{836711a3-5197-4c6c-9bd3-fb4fc3b29b95}{7}" paraid="1713851979"><strong>Indicators of Compromise&nbsp;</strong></p>
